### StreamReader and StreamWriter

`StreamReader` and `StreamWriter` provide efficient character-level I/O for text files.

### StreamWriter (Writing)

```csharp
using StreamWriter writer = new StreamWriter("output.txt");

writer.WriteLine("Hello, World!");
writer.Write("Numbers: ");
writer.Write(42);
writer.WriteLine();
writer.WriteLine($"Today is {DateTime.Now:d}");
// Auto-closes when disposed
```

### StreamWriter Options

```csharp
// Append mode
using StreamWriter writer = new StreamWriter("log.txt", append: true);

// Encoding
using StreamWriter writer = new StreamWriter("file.txt", false, Encoding.UTF8);

// Buffer size
using StreamWriter writer = new StreamWriter("file.txt", false, Encoding.UTF8, 4096);
```

### StreamReader (Reading)

```csharp
using StreamReader reader = new StreamReader("input.txt");

// Read all at once
string all = reader.ReadToEnd();

// Read line by line
string? line;
while ((line = reader.ReadLine()) != null)
{
    Console.WriteLine(line);
}

// Read characters
int char;
while ((char = reader.Read()) != -1)
{
    Console.Write((char)ch);
}
```

### StreamReader Methods

| Method | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `Read()` | Reads next character (-1 if end) |
| `ReadLine()` | Reads next line (null if end) |
| `ReadToEnd()` | Reads all remaining text |
| `Peek()` | Returns next character without consuming |
| `ReadBlock()` | Reads a block of characters |

### Reading Large Files Efficiently

```csharp
using StreamReader reader = new StreamReader("largefile.txt");

// Process line by line (not ReadToEnd)
string? line;
while ((line = reader.ReadLine()) != null)
{
    ProcessLine(line);
}
```

### Reading CSV Example

```csharp
using StreamReader reader = new StreamReader("data.csv");

// Skip header
reader.ReadLine();

while (!reader.EndOfStream)
{
    string line = reader.ReadLine()!;
    string[] fields = line.Split(',');
    Console.WriteLine($"{fields[0]} - {fields[1]}");
}
```

### FileStream (Binary I/O)

```csharp
using FileStream fs = new FileStream("data.bin", FileMode.Create);
byte[] data = Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes("Hello");
fs.Write(data, 0, data.Length);
```

### StreamReader/Writer with Using

```csharp
// Traditional using block
using (var reader = new StreamReader("file.txt"))
{
    string content = reader.ReadToEnd();
}  // Disposed here

// Using declaration (C# 8+)
using var writer = new StreamWriter("file.txt");
writer.WriteLine("Data");
// Disposed at end of scope
```

> **Key Point:** StreamReader/Writer provide efficient text I/O. Always wrap in `using` for proper disposal. Use `ReadLine()` in a loop for large files instead of `ReadToEnd()`. StreamReader supports different encodings. Use `FileStream` for binary data.

### TextReader/TextWriter Base Classes

```csharp
TextReader reader = new StreamReader("file.txt");
TextWriter writer = new StreamWriter("file.txt");
// StringReader/StringWriter for string-based I/O
```

### Asynchronous I/O

```csharp
using StreamReader reader = new StreamReader("file.txt");
string content = await reader.ReadToEndAsync();
```

codeExample:
using System;
using System.IO;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        // Write multiple lines
        using (var writer = new StreamWriter("data.txt"))
        {
            writer.WriteLine("Name,Score");
            writer.WriteLine("Alice,95");
            writer.WriteLine("Bob,87");
            writer.WriteLine("Charlie,92");
        }

        // Read and display
        using var reader = new StreamReader("data.txt");
        Console.WriteLine("File content:");
        string? line;
        while ((line = reader.ReadLine()) != null)
            Console.WriteLine($"  {line}");
    }
}
